    <section class="about-body about-site" aria-labelledby="about-site">
      <h2 id="about-site">About this site</h2>

      <p>
        This website is intentionally simple, transparent, and accessible. It is
        built as a static site, meaning there are no ads, no tracking scripts,
        no paywalls, and no algorithms shaping what you see.
      </p>

      <p>
        The Liberation and Inclusion Translation is offered freely online
        because access to sacred texts and interpretive work should not be
        restricted by income, institutional affiliation, or geography.
      </p>

      <p>
        This site is a work in progress. Text, notes, and structure may evolve
        as the translation continues and feedback is incorporated. Revisions are
        made carefully and publicly, with the aim of improved clarity, accuracy,
        and readability.
      </p>

      <h3>How to use this site</h3>

      <p>
        If you want to read from beginning to end, you can. If you prefer to
        move between passages, books, and themes, that works too. You do not
        need to follow a fixed order or agree with every translation choice to
        engage meaningfully with the text.
      </p>

      <p>
        Use the <a href="/read">Read Now</a> page to choose a book and chapter directly.
        It also shows which books are available now and which are still coming later.
      </p>

      <p>
        You can read individual passages on their own, move between books, or
        compare the translation here with other versions you already know. The
        navigation and structure are meant to support curiosity rather than
        enforce a particular path.
      </p>

      <p>
        Footnotes are an important part of the translation, but they are
        optional. Some readers will want to read straight through and return to
        the notes later; others will move back and forth frequently. Both
        approaches are valid.
      </p>

      <p>
        This site can be used for study, reflection, group discussion, teaching,
        or quiet reading. It is not designed for speed or volume, but for
        attentiveness. Taking your time here is part of how the translation is
        meant to be read.
      </p>
      <p class="about-back">
        <a href="#top">Back to top</a>
      </p>
